<subSubSection pageNumber="276" type="discussion">
<paragraph pageNumber="276">
<emphasis italics="true" pageNumber="276">Note:</emphasis>
See discussion by Mathew (
<emphasis italics="true" pageNumber="276">Rev.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authority="Sect. Allium" class="Liliopsida" family="Amaryllidaceae" genus="Allium" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asparagales" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="section" section="Allium">
Allium 
<emphasis italics="true" pageNumber="276">Sect.</emphasis>
Allium
</taxonomicName>
: 144. 1996), who acknowledges that, because of its type, 
<taxonomicName authority="L." authorityName="Linnaeus" authorityYear="1756" class="Liliopsida" family="Amaryllidaceae" genus="Allium" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asparagales" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="ascalonicum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageNumber="276">A. ascalonicum</emphasis>
L.
</taxonomicName>
is the earliest name for 
<taxonomicName authority="Boiss. Following Stearn" authorityName="Boiss. Following Stearn" authorityYear="1882" class="Liliopsida" family="Amaryllidaceae" genus="Allium" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asparagales" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="hierochuntinum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageNumber="276">A. hierochuntinum</emphasis>
Boiss. Following Stearn
</taxonomicName>
(in 
<emphasis italics="true" pageNumber="276">Bull. Brit. Mus. (Nat. Hist.), Bot.</emphasis>
2: 181. 1960), he informally rejected the former because it has been applied more or less continuously since 1762 to a well-known cultivar of 
<taxonomicName authority="L. However" authorityName="Linnaeus" authorityYear="1753" class="Liliopsida" family="Amaryllidaceae" genus="Allium" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asparagales" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="cepa">
<emphasis italics="true" pageNumber="276">A. cepa</emphasis>
L. However
</taxonomicName>
, no formal rejection proposal has been made.
</paragraph>
